==Most prominent summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Most prominent summits}}
{{main|List of the most prominent summits of the United States}}
{{see also|List of the ultra-prominent summits of the United States}}
Of the 50 most prominent summits of the United States, only Denali exceeds {{convert|5000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of topographic prominence, three peaks exceed {{convert|4000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}}, ten peaks exceed {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}}, 45 peaks exceed {{convert|2000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}}, and all 50 peaks exceed {{convert|1932|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.  All of these peaks are [[List of Ultras of the United States|ultra-prominent summits]].

Of these 50 peaks, 27 are located in Alaska, five in Washington, five in California, three in Hawai{{okina}}i, three in Wyoming, two in Nevada, two in Oregon, and one each in Colorado, Utah, and Arizona.  Three of these summits lie on the international border between Alaska and Yukon, and one lies on the international border between Alaska and British Columbia.
{{clear}}
