[[File:Parana traps.JPG|thumb|300px|A cliff at the Paraná Magmatic Province. Rio do Rastro, Santa Catarina. One can see the near vertical escarpment of silicic succession from waning-stage volcanism.]] The '''Paraná-Etendeka traps''' (or '''Paraná and Etendeka Plateau'''; or '''Paraná and Etendeka Province''') comprise a [[large igneous province]] that includes both the main Paraná [[Trap rock |traps]] (in [[Paraná Basin]], a [[South American]] [[geological basin]]) as well as the smaller severed portions of the [[flood basalt]]s at the Etendeka traps (in northwest [[Namibia]] and southwest [[Angola]]). The original basalt flows occurred 128 to 138 million years ago. The province had a post-flow surface area of 1.5 x 10<sup>6</sup> km² (580,000 miles²) and an original volume projected to be in excess of 2.3 x 10<sup>6</sup> km³.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Sur l'âge des trapps basaltiques (On the ages of flood basalt events) |first=Vincent E. |last=Courtillot |first2=Paul R. |last2=Renneb |journal=Comptes Rendus Geoscience |volume=335 |issue=1 |date=January 2003 |pages=113–140 |doi=10.1016/S1631-0713(03)00006-3|bibcode=2003CRGeo.335..113C }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first=R.V. |last=Fodor |first2=E.H. |last2=McKee |first3=A. |last3=Roisenberg |title=Age distribution of Serra Geral (Paraná) flood basalts, southern Brazil |journal=Journal of South American Earth Sciences |volume=2 |issue=4 |year=1989 |pages=343–349 |doi=10.1016/0895-9811(89)90012-6 |bibcode = 1989JSAES...2..343F }}</ref>
== Geodynamics == The basalt samples at Paraná and Etendeka have an age of about 132&nbsp;Ma, during the [[Valanginian]] stage of the [[Early Cretaceous]].<ref name=Ar>{{cite journal |last1=Stewart |first1=Kathy |last2=Turner |first2=Simon |last3=Kelley|first3=Simon |last4=Hawkesworth |first4=Chris|last5=Kirstein|first5=Linda|last6=Mantovani |first6=Marta |date=1996 |title=3-D, <sup>40</sup>Ar-<sup>39Ar</sup> geochronology in the Paraná continental flood basalt province |url= |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=143 |issue=1-4 |pages=95–109 |doi=10.1016/0012-821X(96)00132-X |bibcode=1996E&PSL.143...95S }}</ref> Indirectly, the rifting and [[Extension (geology)|extension]] are probably the origin of the Paraná and Etendeka traps and it could be the origin of the [[Gough Island|Gough]] and [[Tristan da Cunha]] Islands as well, as they are connected by the [[Walvis Ridge]] (Gough/[[Tristan hotspot]]). The seamounts of the [[Rio Grande Rise]] (25°S to 35°S) that go eastwards from the Paraná side<ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Neill |first=C. |last2=Müller |first2=R. D. |last3=Steinberger |first3=B. |title=Revised Indian plate rotations based on the motion of Indian Ocean hotspots |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=215 |pages=151–168 |year=2003 |url=http://www.earthbyte.org/people/dietmar/Pdf/Muller-etal-hotspots-Geology1993.pdf |bibcode=2003E&PSL.215..151O |doi=10.1016/S0012-821X(03)00368-6 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726011820/http://www.earthbyte.org/people/dietmar/Pdf/Muller-etal-hotspots-Geology1993.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-26 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=O'Connor |first=J. M. |last2=le Roex |first2=A. P. |year=1992 |title=South Atlantic hot spot-plume systems. 1: Distribution of volcanism in time and space |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=113 |pages=343–364 |doi=10.1016/0012-821X(92)90138-L|bibcode = 1992E&PSL.113..343O }}</ref> are part of this traps system.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/brazil/10040685/Brazilian-Atlantis-found.html Brazilian 'Atlantis' found - Geologists have announced the discovery of what has been dubbed the 'Brazilian Atlantis', some 900 miles from Rio.], Donna Bowater, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 May 2013</ref>
== Description == Interpretations of geochemistry, including [[isotope]]s, have led geologists to conclude that the magmas forming the traps and associated [[igneous rock]]s originated by [[partial melting|melting]] of [[asthenosphere|asthenosphic mantle]] due to the arrival of a [[mantle plume]] to the base of Earth's [[lithosphere]]. Then much of the magma was [[crustal contamination|contaminated]] with [[continental crust|crustal materials]] prior to their eruption. Some [[plutonic rock]]s related to the traps escaped crustal contamination reflecting more directly the source of the magmas in the mantle.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen-Smith |first1=T.M. |last2=Ashwal |first2=L.D.|last3=Sudo |first3=M. |last4=Trumbull |first4=R.B. |date=2017 |title=Age and Petrogenesis of the Doros Complex, Namibia, and Implications for Early Plume-derived Melts in the Paraná–Etendeka LIP |url=https://academic.oup.com/petrology/article/58/3/423/3866491/Age-and-Petrogenesis-of-the-Doros-Complex-Namibia |journal=[[Journal of Petrology]] |volume=58 |issue=3 |pages=423–442 |doi=10.1093/petrology/egx021 |access-date= |bibcode=2017JPet...58..423O }}</ref>
A type of rock called [[ignimbrite]] is found in some parts of the traps indicating [[explosive eruption|explosive]] volcanic activity. The Paraná Traps possibly contains the site of the single [[List of largest volcanic eruptions|largest explosive volcanic eruption]] known in Earth's history.<ref name="Bryan et al 2010">{{cite journal |author=Scott E. Bryan |author2=Ingrid Ukstins Peate |author3=David W. Peate |author4=Stephen Self |author5=Dougal A. Jerram |author6=Michael R. Mawby |author7=J.S. Marsh |author8=Jodie A. Miller |title=The largest volcanic eruptions on Earth|journal=Earth-Science Reviews |volume=102 |pages=207|year=2010|doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2010.07.001|bibcode=2010ESRv..102..207B}}</ref>
