A '''tangie''' (or ''tongie''{{r|"DOSL"}}) is a shape-shifting sea spirit in the [[folklore]] of the [[Orkney]] and [[Shetland Islands]] in the British Isles.{{sfnp|Briggs|2002|p=280|ps=none}} A sea horse or [[merman]], it takes on the appearance of either a <!--rough-haired pony-->horse or an aged man.{{r|"DOSL"}}{{r|"Edmonston"}} Usually described as being covered with seaweed<!--or shells in its mane-->, its name derives from "tang"{{efn|Cognate with Old Norse and Faroese ''þang'' and Danish ''tang''.}} or seaweed of the genus ''[[Fucus]]''.{{r|"DOSL"}}{{r|"Edmonston"}}

It is known for terrorizing lonely travellers, especially young women on roads at night near the [[lochs]], whom it will abduct and devour under the water.

Similar yet distinctive from the nogel, a tangie is able to cause derangement in humans and animals.{{sfnp|Teit|1918|p=187|ps=none}}

The tangie plays a major role in the Shetland legend of Black Eric, a sheep rustler. The tangie he rode gave him supernatural assistance when he raided and harassed surrounding [[crofts]]. In his final battle with crofter Sandy Breamer, Black Eric fell to his death in the sea. The tangie then continued to terrorize the area, particularly the young women he was hoping to abduct.{{sfnp|Lamont-Brown|1996|p=84|ps=none}}

